re the people even questions connected with the %0a%3c various methods employed in agriculture, and wiU be seen in %0a%3c what way men were accustomed to speak out in their o^\^l %0a%3c defence. C. Furius ChresiH^us, a freedman, having found him¬ %0a%3c self able, from a very small piece of land, to raise far more %0a%3c abundant harvests than his neighbours could from the largest %0a%3c farms, became the object of very considerable jealousy among %0a%3c them, and was accordingly accused of enticing away the crops %0a%3c of others by the practice of sorcery. Upon this, a day was %0a%3c named by Spurius Calvinus, the curule aedile, for his appear¬ %0a%3c ance. Apprehensive of being condemned, when the question %0a%3c came to be put to the vote among the tribes, he had all his %0a%3c implements of husbandry brought into the Forum, together %0a%3c with his farm servants, robust, well-conditioned, and well-clad %0a%3c people, Piso says. The iron tools were of first-rate quality, %0a%3c the mattocks were stout and strong, the plough-shares ponde¬ %0a%3c rous and substantial, and the oxen sleek and in prime condi¬ %0a%3c tion. When all this had been done, “ Here, Koman citi¬ %0a%3c zens,” said he, “ are my implements of magic; but it is impos¬ %0a%3c sible for me to exhibit to your view, or to bring into this %0a%3c Forum, those midnight toils of mine, those early watchings, %0a%3c those sweats, and those fatigues.” Upon this, by the unani¬ %0a%3c mous voice of the people, he was immediately acquitted. %0a%3c Agriculture, in fact, depends upon the expenditure of labour %0a%3c and exertion; and hence it is that the ancients were in the %0a%3c habit of saying, that it is the eye of the master that does more %0a%3c towards fertilizing a field than anything else. %0a%3c %0a%3c We shall give the rest of these precepts in their appropriate %0a%3c places, according as we find them adapted to each variety of %0a%3c cultivation ; but in the meantime we must not omit some of a %0a%