absurdity. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 30.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c THE BEA2T. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 45 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c The bean is the first leguminous plant that is sown; that %0a%3c being done before the setting of the Vergilias, in order that it %0a%3c may pass the winter in the ground. Virgil^ recommends that %0a%3c it should be sown in spring, according to the usage of the parts %0a%3c of Italj near the Padus: but most people prefer the bean that %0a%3c has been sown early to that of only three months’ growth; %0a%3c for, in the former case, the pods as well as the stalk afibid a %0a%3c most agreeable fodder for cattle. When in blossoiii more par¬ %0a%3c ticularly, the bean requires water; but after the blossom has %0a%3c passed off, it stands in need of but very little. It fertilizes®^ %0a%3c the grouud in which it has been sown as well as any manure; %0a%3c hence it is that in the neighbourhood of Thessaly and Ma¬ %0a%3c cedonia, as soon 'as it begins to blossom, they turn up®® the %0a%3c ground. %0a%3c %0a%3c The bean, too, grows wild in most countries, as in those %0a%3c islands of the Northern Ocean, for instance, which for that %0a%3c reason have been called by us the “Pabarige.”®® In Mauritania, %0a%3c also, it is found in a wild state in various parts, but so remark¬ %0a%3c ably hard that it will never become soft by boiling. %0a%3c %0a%3c In Egypt there is a kind of bean®® which grows upon a %0a%3c thorny stalk; for which reason the crocodiles avoid it, being %0a%3c apprehensive of danger to their eyes. This stalk is four %0a%3c cubits in length, and its thickness, at the very most, that of %0a%3c the finger : were it not for the absence of articulations in it, %0a%3c it would resemble a soft reed in appearance. The head is %0a%3c similar to that of the poppy, being of a rose colour : the beans %0a%3c enclosed in this head are not above thirty in number; the %0a%3c leaves are large, and the fruit is bitter and odoriferous. The %0a%3c root, however, is