er, a native of Chios. He is said to have claimed %0a%3c the discovery of the obliquity of the Ecliptic. %0a%3c %0a%3c Probably Zenon of Elea, one of the most famous philosophers of %0a%3c antiquity. All of his works had perished at a very early period. %0a%3c %0a%3c An Athenian astronomer, the friend and assistant of Meton, about %0a%3c 430 B.c. %0a%3c %0a%3c An astronomer mentioned by Censorinus, as having corrected the in¬ %0a%3c tercalation of Cleostratus. Nothing further appears to be known of liim. %0a%3c %0a%3c Eor Hecataeus of Miletus, see B. iv. for Hecatseus of Abdera, %0a%3c see B. vi. ®* See end of B. iv. %0a%3c %0a%3c 99 See end of B. ii. ® See end of B. ii. %0a%3c %0a%3c * A native of Soli, or else Tarsus, in Cilicia. He was the author of %0a%3c two Greek astronomical poems which have come down to us. He flou¬ %0a%3c rished about B.c. 270. %0a%3c %0a%3c 3 Nothing can be said of him with any degree of historical certainty. %0a%3c By the Persians he was called Zerdusht, and was said to have been the %0a%3c founder of the Magian religion. There were several works in Greek %0a%3c hearing his name, but which, no doubt, were forgeries of a later age than %0a%3c that usually assigned to him. %0a%3c %0a%3c ■* He is mentioned in c. 70 of this Book, as writing a letter to Anlio- %0a%3c chus, king of Syria; but nothing further seems to be known of him. %0a---%0a> vol 4 [[https://archive.org/details/57011150RX4.nlm.nih.gov|#]]%0a> %0a> vol 5 [[https://archive.org/details/57011150RX5.nlm.nih.gov|#]]%0a> %0a> vol 6 [[https://archive.org/details/57011150RX6.nlm.nih.gov|#]]%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
